$CRIN CRF1

                      ^      CELL COORDINATES       ^

         Use the following format to reference a cell:

               [column number, row number]

         For example, the cell containing the label "JAN", in column 2 
         and row 1, is referred to as cell [2,1]:

                      /....0/....1/....2/....3
                     0                       
                     1               JAN
                     2

         Formulas require square brackets, but most commands do not.
         You can also use column and row names instead of numbers if
         the /OPTION NAMES command is enabled.  
         Reference: {/ON}1. /OPTION NAMES.

$CRFRM CRF1

                        ^ CELL REFERENCES IN FORMULAS ^

         The following example shows a simple formula that includes two
         cell references:

         Formula: [1,0] + [1,2] + 5.2

   
               This formula adds the value of cell [1,0] to the
               value of cell [1,2] and then adds 5.2 to the first
               result.

                       /....0/....1/....2/....3
                      0         4.3
                      1 
                      2         3.2

         Value of Formula When Recalculated: 4.3 + 3.2 + 5.2 = 12.7 

$CRFX CRF1

                         ^                       ^
                         ^ FIXED CELL REFERENCES ^
                         ^                       ^

     A fixed cell reference in a formula does not change when you move 
     the formula to other cells (by using the /COPY or /STORAGE PASTE 
     commands).  The dollar sign ($) preceding the column or row 
     reference indicates a fixed cell reference.  

     The following is a fixed cell reference:  [$1,$2]

$CRRL CRF1
        
                          ^                          ^
                          ^ RELATIVE CELL REFERENCES ^
                          ^                          ^

         Relative references adjust to any worksheet location.  To
         enter a relative cell reference in a formula, you enclose 
         the column and row coordinates in square brackets.

         Use a relative cell reference when you want the cell reference
         in a formula to adjust whenever the location of the formula 
         changes (when you use the /COPY or /STORAGE PASTE commands).

         The adjustment maintains a constant number of columns and rows
         between the cell in which the formula is located and the cell
         referenced by the formula.

         The following is a relative cell reference:  [1,2]

# CRF1

                       ^ RELATIVE CELL REFERENCES (2) ^

         For example, suppose cell [3,4] contains the following formula:

                                [2,4] * 12 

           ______________________________________________________________
           | New    | Formula     |                                     |
           | Cell   | after /COPY | Comment                             |
           |------------------------------------------------------------|
           | [3,5]  | [2,5]*12    | Each formula continues to reference |
           | [4,5]  | [3,5]*12    | the cell in the previous column,    |
           | [15,6] | [14,6]*12   | same row                            |
           --------------------------------------------------------------

$CRMX CRF1

                           ^                       ^
                           ^ MIXED CELL REFERENCES ^
                           ^                       ^

         Cell references can be mixed, so that one coordinate is fixed
         and the other is relative.  For example, the cell reference [$0,1]
         contains a fixed column coordinate and a relative row coordinate.
         The cell reference [0,$1] contains a relative column coordinate
         and a fixed row coordinate.

         When a mixed reference is copied, the fixed coordinate remains
         constant, and the relative coordinate changes.

         By using mixed cell references, you can maintain the same number of
         columns ^or^ rows between the cell containing your formula and the
         cell referenced by your formula.  This is useful, for example, when
         you want to multiply a number by a value from a list entered in a
         column or row.

# CRF1

                         ^ MIXED CELL REFERENCES (2) ^


         If cell [3,4] contains the formula:

                            [$2,4]*12 

           _____________________________________________________________
           |        | Formula     |                                    |
           | Cell   | after /COPY | Comment                            |
           |-----------------------------------------------------------|
           | [4,5]  | [$2,5]*12   | The fixed reference to column 2    |
           |        |             | remains unchanged in the formula.  |
           | [16,17]| [$2,17]*12  | The relative row reference changes |
           |        |             | as the row changes.                |
           -------------------------------------------------------------

$CRPT CRF1

                              ^                 ^
                              ^ POINT-TO METHOD ^
                              ^                 ^

         POINT-TO allows you to enter a cell reference without typing
         in the coordinates.  You can use POINT-TO to enter cell
         references and ranges in both commands and formulas. 

         To use the POINT-TO feature:

           1. Press <DOWN-ARROW>

           2. Move the cell cursor to the desired cell.

           3. Type one of the keys listed in the table on the NEXT screen.

# CRF1

    <CR>     Enters a relative cell reference. Example: [4,4]

     $       Enters a fixed cell reference.  Example: [$4,$4]

     .       Enters a relative reference, followed by two periods to
             indicate a range. You then specify the end of the range.
             Example: [4,4]..

     C       Enters the column coordinate as a fixed reference and
             the row coordinate as a relative reference.  Example: [$4,4]

     R       Enters the row coordinate as a fixed reference and the
             column coordinate as a relative reference.  Example: [4,$4] 

  + - / *    Enters a relative reference, followed by the specified
             specified arithmetic operator.  Example: [4,4] + 

     )       Enters a reference that is terminated with a ). Example: [4,4])

$CRRG CRF1

                          ^                           ^
                          ^        CELL RANGES        ^
                          ^                           ^

   A cell range is the cell coordinate or coordinates that indicate 
   the cell's worksheet location.  

   A cell range can be:

           {CRRGS}1. A single cell
           {CRRGC}2. A contiguous group of cells
           {CRRFN}3. A non-contiguous groups of cells

    Several 20/20 commands, such as /COPY and /MODIFY BLANK, require
    that you specify a cell range. You can also use cell ranges in
    several 20/20 functions, such as SUM and AVG.

$CRRGS CRRG

                                ^             ^
                                ^ SINGLE CELL ^
                                ^             ^


          To specify a single cell range, simply enter the cell's 
          coordinates.  If the /OPTION NAMES command is enabled,
          you can also enter the cell's names.
          
          For example:

              [3,4]   or   [MAY,DUE]

          You can also use the POINT-TO method.

              {CRPT}1. POINT-TO
              {/ON}2. /OPTION NAMES

$CRRGC CRRG

                         ^                           ^
                         ^ CONTIGUOUS GROUP OF CELLS ^
                         ^                           ^


 Contiguous Ranges     A contiguous range is any rectangular array
                       of cells. To specify a contiguous range, use:

                         {CRRGR}1. The Rectangle Method

                                   or

                         {CRRGM}2. The Column and Row Method

$CRRGR CRRGC
            
                           ^ THE RECTANGLE METHOD ^

         Enter only the top left and bottom right cells in the range.
         Note that you can use the POINT-TO method. (See POINT-TO).

              ______________________________________________
              | Range Specification | Includes cells       |
              |____________________________________________|
              | [0,10]..[2,10]      | [0,10] [1,10] [2,10] |
              |                     |                      |
              | [0,10]..[0,12]      | [0,10]               |
              |                     | [0,11]               |
              |                     | [0,12]               |
              |                     |                      |
              | [0,10]..[2,11]      | [0,10] [1,10] [2,10] |
              |                     | [0,11] [1,11] [2,11] |
              |_____________________|______________________|

$CRRGM CRRGC

                          ^ COLUMN AND ROW METHOD ^
                          ^                       ^

         Use the first and last column coordinates, followed by the
         first and last row coordinates.

                  ______________________________________________
                 | Range Specification | Includes cells         |
                 |_____________________|________________________|
                 | 0..2,10             | [0,10] [1,10] [2,10]   |
                 |                     |                        |
                 | 0,10..12            | [0,10]                 |
                 |                     | [0,11]                 |
                 |                     | [0,12]                 |
                 |                     |                        |
                 | 0..2,10..11         | [0,10]  [1,10]  [2,10] |
                 |                     | [0,11]  [1,11]  [2,11] |
                  ----------------------------------------------

$CRRFN CRRG

                       ^                                ^
                       ^ NON-CONTIGUOUS GROUPS OF CELLS ^
                       ^                                ^

        A non-contiguous range skips columns and/or rows between its corner
        cells.  You specify a non-contiguous range by placing the list of
        included columns or rows in parentheses, separated by commas.  For
        example, the following range has non-contiguous columns and rows.

                    ____________________________________________
                   | Range Specification | Includes cells       |
                   |--------------------------------------------|
                   | (1,3),(2,4)         | [1,2]   [3,2]        |
                   |                     | [1,4]   [3,4]        |
                    --------------------------------------------

        You can use contiguous or noncontiguous ranges with commands. 
        However, 20/20 functions accept only contiguous ranges.

$CRFN CRF1

                        ^                                   ^
                        ^ REFERENCING A LABEL AS A FILENAME ^
                        ^                                   ^

         The /STORAGE READ, /STORAGE IMPORT COMMAND, and /STORAGE PASTE
         commands permit using a cell reference as a filename.

         You can use a cell reference as a filename for these commands if:

                 1) The contents of the cell is text data, and
   
                 2) The text data is the name of a stored file.

$CRCN CRF1

                            ^                      ^
                            ^ CELL NAME REFERENCES ^
                            ^                      ^

         Cell naming allows you to reference a cell by column and/or row
         name, rather than by numeric coordinates.

         Use the /OPTION NAMES command to enable naming.  /OPTION NAMES
         designates any label in row 0 as a column name and any label in
         column 0 as a row name.

         By enabling cell names, you can refer to data by common sense
         terms, such as FEB,SALES.  Cell names are especially useful in 
         conjunction with the /STORAGE LINK, /TOOLS DATABASE, /MODIFY 
         MOVE and /GRAPH commands, and with the <GOTO> method of cell 
         cursor movement.

         Reference:    {/ON}1. /OPTION NAMES

$CMD1 BAS

                              ^                   ^
                              ^ THE SCREEN HEADER ^
                              ^                   ^

         The screen header contains helpful information about your worksheet
         and consists of three lines. For example:

 {CMDS}1. The Status Line     - [Col: 2 Row: 9] N (F2)  103.00
 {CMDE}2. The Edit Line       - Copy Modify ^Edit^ Format Default Storage Print
 {CMDH}3. The Mini-HELP line  - Edit the contents of a cell

$CMDS CMD1

                              ^ THE STATUS LINE ^

                   ^     [Col: 2 Row: 9] N (F2)  103.00     ^

 The top line of the 20/20 terminal screen is the Status line. This line
 contains information about the cell in which the cursor is currently located.

 The cell indicator, located at the left corner of the Status line, identifies
 the location of the cell cursor by its column and row coordinates.

 The letter to the right indicates the kind of data contained in the current
 cell - N (number), L (label), or F (formula).  A blank cell lists no letter
 here.

 The characters enclosed by parentheses indicate the format (set by the
 /FORMAT or /DEFAULT commands) for numerical data entered in the current
 cell. The initial setting is (F0) -- which means "Fixed format with 0
 decimal places displayed".

# CMD1

                               ^ CELL CONTENTS ^

        The last item on the Status line is the data that is contained
        in the cell.  For example:

                  [Col: 2 Row: 9] N (F2)   103.00

        In this case, it is the fixed decimal number 103.  Notice the two
        decimal places in the display -- specified by the (F2) format.

$CMDE CMD1

                             ^ THE EDIT LINE ^

 The second line in the Header is the Edit line. Initially, this line displays:

         Ready:

 You can enter data or a command at Ready:.  To enter a 20/20 command, type 
 a slash (/).   The Edit line then displays a list of the top level commands.
 To select a command from this list, type the initial letter of the command;
 or, use an arrow key to move to the command, and type <CR>.  If you select 
 the /EDIT command, the Edit line displays:  

         /EDIT:

 When you type a label, number, or formula, the Edit line displays:

         Entry:

$CMDH CMD1

                             ^                    ^
                             ^ THE MINI-HELP LINE ^
                             ^                    ^

         The third line in the Header is the Mini-HELP line.  When you
         type a slash (/), this line contains a brief description of the
         highlighted command.  For example, the Mini-HELP description of 
         the /COPY command is:

                Copy a range of cells into a new range 

         Note: If data entered on the Edit line requires more than one
         display line, the overflow appears on the Mini-HELP line.

$EDT1 BAS

                      ^                             ^
                      ^     USING THE EDIT LINE     ^
                      ^                             ^


         You can edit, and move around the Edit line (while /EDIT: or
         ENTRY: is displayed), by using the following keys:  

         <DEL>     Deletes the character under the cursor (usually the last
                   character typed) and moves the cursor back one space.

         <RT>      Moves the cursor to the right, without erasing any 
                   characters.

         <LF>      Moves the cursor to the left, without erasing any 
                   characters.

