$DEP FUNCS

                           ^ DEPR(type,period,life) ^
     
     Calculates the four most commonly used depreciation functions:
     CRossover, DOuble-declining, SUm-of-digits, and STraight-line.

     The type is indicated by two letters, in quotation marks -- "CR",
     "DO", "SU", or "ST".  The valid types, their abbreviations and 
     definitions are listed in the chart on the NEXT screen.  The period 
     is the period for which the depreciation is being calculated.  The 
     life is the total number of periods over which the article is 
     depreciated.

     To determine depreciated amount for any given period, multiply
     the result of the DEPR function by the value of the article.

     Example:  A piece of equipment with a lifetime of five years costs
               $15,000.  The depreciation by the double-declining method in
               year three is given by the formula:   15000*DEPR("DO",3,5)

#DEP2 FUNCS

             ----------------------------------------------------------
             | Straight- | "ST"    | 1/life                           |
             |  Line     |         |                                  |
             |-----------|---------|----------------------------------|
             | Sum-of-   | "SU"    | (life+1-period)*2/(life*(1+life))|
             | Digits    |         |                                  |
             |-----------|---------|----------------------------------|
             | Double-   | "DO"    | 2/life of undepreciated balance, |
             | Declining |         | each period except the last.     |
             |           |         | Depreciation in the last period  |
             |           |         | is the remaining undepreciated   |
             |           |         | balance.                         |
             |-----------|---------|----------------------------------|
             | Cross-    | "CR"    | Uses a double-declining formula  |
             | over      |         | until straight-line (applied to  |
             |           |         | the remaining amount) increases  |
             |           |         | the depreciation.                |
             ----------------------------------------------------------

