$FVZ FUNCS

                          ^ FV(interest rate,range) - 1 ^

  Calculates the Future Value of cash flow.  The interest rate must be given
  in decimal form (.12 for 12%) and can be a cell reference.

  The range is the series of values for the cash flow at regular intervals.
  If the values of the cells given by the range are called V1, V2, ...Vn,
  then:
             FV(interest rate, range)

  is equivalent to..

             V1(1+rate)**n + V2(1+rate)**(n-1) + ... + Vn(1+rate)

  where ** means "raised to the power"

  If the interest rate is less than or equal to -1.0 (-100%), then the value
  of the function is ERR.

#FVZ2 FUNCS

                       ^                             ^
                       ^ FV(interest rate,range) - 2 ^
                       ^                             ^


    Example:  

    With a 12% interest rate, if [4,7] = $20.00 and [5,7] = $25.00, then 
    FV(.12,[4..5,7]) = $53.09
                       

$IFZ FUNCS

                       ^                                  ^
                       ^ IF(logical expression,then,else) ^
                       ^                                  ^

         If the value of the logical expression is TRUE (or any non-zero
         value), IF returns the value "then".  If the value of the logical
         expression is FALSE (or zero), IF returns the value "else".

         The values of "then" and "else" can be:

           o  numbers
           o  formulas
           o  references to cells that contain formulas, labels, or numbers

         For example:   IF([3,10]>=2000,[2,12]*.43,0)

$INDX FUNCS

                          ^                         ^
                          ^ INDEX(expression,range) ^
                          ^                         ^

     Operates with an expression and a range of numbers in ascending order.   
     The first value in the range has an INDEX of 0, the next has an INDEX 
     of 1, and so on.  INDEX looks up the value of the expression in the 
     range until it comes to a number larger than the expression and returns
     the index of the preceding value in the range.

     INDEX is an expanded LOOKUP -- it allows you to perform the LOOKUP 
     function on non-adjacent ranges, when used in conjunction with SEL.

