$LOO FUNCS

                           ^                          ^
                           ^ LOOKUP(expression,range) ^
                           ^                          ^

         Operates with an expression, a contiguous range of cells, and a set
         of adjacent cells.  The contents of the range cells should be in
         ascending order.  20/20 matches the "expression" against cells in
         the "range", and finds the cell whose value is closest to the value
         of the expression without exceeding it.  LOOKUP returns the value of
         the corresponding cell in the adjacent range.  If the first cell in
         the range is greater than the expression, 20/20 returns the value ERR.

         The position of the set of adjacent cells is predefined by 20/20.
         20/20 looks below or to the right of the "range" row or column.  The
         adjacent cells can contain values or labels.

         See NEXT screen for an example of LOOKUP applications.

#LOO2 FUNCS


                     ^ LOOKUP(expression,range) -2- ^

         In the function LOOKUP(45,[0..5,10]), the range is the part
         of row 10 from column 0 to 5.  20/20 assumes the set of 
         adjacent cells is in row 11 from column 0 to 5.

                     10    10    20     30     40   50   60
                     11  0.05  0.05  0.075  0.075  0.1  0.1

         LOOKUP matches the value 45 against each cell (starting with 
         cell [0,10]) until it reaches cell [4,10].  LOOKUP then returns
         the value of 0.075, taken from cell [3,11].

$LSQ FUNCS

                           ^                         ^
                           ^ LSQ(type,range1,range2) ^
                           ^                         ^




         Performs a linear least-squares analysis of data.

         The valid types, their abbreviations, and definitions are
         listed in the chart on the NEXT screen.

#LSQ2 FUNCS

             ---------------------------------------------------------
             | TYPE     | ABBREV. | DEFINITION                       |
             ---------------------------------------------------------
             | Slope    | "SL"    | The value of 'b' in the fitted   |
             |          |         | equation y = a + bx.             |
             |----------|---------|----------------------------------|
             | Intercept| "IN"    | The value of 'a' in the fitted   |
             |          |         | equation y = a + bx.             |
             |----------|---------|----------------------------------|
             | Correlat-| "CO"    | An estimate of how much improve- |
             | ion      |         | ment the linear equation gives   |
             |          |         | over simply using the mean of the|
             |          |         | y-values as the estimate for y.  |
             |          |         | A correlation coefficient of zero|
             |          |         | means no improvement (and no     |
             |          |         | correlation); a value of one     |
             |          |         | means perfect correlation.       |
             ---------------------------------------------------------

#LSQ3 FUNCS

                         ^ LSQ(type,range1,range2) -3- ^

         Indicate the type by entering the first two letters (SL, IN,
         CO), enclosed in double quotes (").  Any additional letters, if
         included, are ignored.

         Range1 is a single row or column of at least two elements
         containing the y-values to be fit.  Range2 contains the x-values
         of the least-squares fit and must contain the same number of
         elements as range1. Range2 can be omitted.  If range2 is absent,
         then it is assumed to begin at zero and to continue in
         increments of one.


#LSQ4 FUNCS            

                       ^ LSQ(type,range1,range2) -4- ^

 
         For example:  

         If [4,2] = 11, [4,3] = 12, [5,2] = 17, and [5,3] = 9, then:

         Type                 Formula 
         ----                 -------
         Correlation:         LSQ("CO",[4,2..3],[5,2..3]) = 0.5000
         Intercept:           LSQ("IN",[4,2..3],[5,2..3]) = 2.5000
         Slope:               LSQ("SL",[4,2..3],[5,2..3]) = 0.5000

