    BAR          -  Causes the cell to become part of a bar graph display.

    , (Comma)    -  Displays and prints commas for all numeric values
                    greater than 999 or less than -999.

    Default      -  Cancels the current cell format, and restores the
                    format set by the /DEFAULT command.

    $ (Dollars   -  Displays numeric values in dollars and cents form,
      and Cents)    with comma notation.

    EXPONENTIAL  -  Displays numeric values in exponential (scientific)
                    form.

                 See NEXT screen for more.

#/FO2 /F

                          ^ FORMAT OPTIONS - 2 ^

   ( (Financial) -  Displays negative numbers in parentheses, with comma
                    notation.

   FIXED         -  Displays numeric values in decimal form.

   GRAPH         -  Causes the cell's value to be displayed as a series of
                    plus or minus signs.

   INVISIBLE     -  Suppresses the display of the cell's value.  This format
                    is useful for intermediate results that should not
                    appear in a finished report.

                 See NEXT screen for more.

#/FO3 /F

                          ^ FORMAT OPTIONS - 3 ^

   % (Percent)  -  Displays a numeric value as a percentage.  The value 
                   displayed is the cell value multiplied by 100, with 
                   a percent sign appended.

   LOCK         -  LOCK: Locks an individual cell for keyboard entry.
                -  UNLOCK: Unlocks an individual cell for keyboard entry.
                -  DEFAULT: Returns the current cell to /DEFAULT status.

   TRUE         -  Causes the cell's value to be displayed as either TRUE
                   or blank.

   WIDTH        -  Sets the width (number of spaces) of an individual col-
                   umn.  The default width is eight spaces.

$/G /

                                ^ GRAPH ^

       Creates graphic images of worksheet data.
   
       When you issue a /GRAPH command, 20/20 displays the graph options. 
       These designate the kind (form) of graph, the data you want to
       graph, and the window to display the graph.

       Most /GRAPH options include defaults.  These defaults allow you
       to select an option by simply typing <CR>.
         
       The /GRAPH options are:

           {/GV} 1. VIEW        {/GP} 2. PLOT        {/GF} 3. FORM
           {/GR} 4. RANGE       {/GW} 5. WINDOW      {/GG} 6. GRID
           {/GO} 7. ORDER       {/GT} 8. TITLE       {/GS} 9. SUBT
           {/GL}10. LABELS      {/GH}11. HEADING     {/GA}12. AXIS
           {/GN}13. NAME

$/GV /G

                          ^                    ^
                          ^ VIEW SPECIFICATION ^
                          ^                    ^


      VIEW  -  Displays the created graph in the current window.  If you
               have not fully specified the graph you want, 20/20 uses 
               default graph options as needed.  

       NOTE:  You can view graphics only on a graphics terminal. Use /OPTION 
       TERMINAL to set the terminal type.  Reference: {/OT}1. /OPTION TERMINAL


$/GP /G

                          ^                    ^
                          ^ PLOT SPECIFICATION ^
                          ^                    ^

      PLOT -  Draws a single graph on the entire worksheet screen
              after you specify a plotter, printer, or color monitor 
              as a graphics output device.  The PLOT options are:

                       {/GPG}1. Graph
                       {/GPW}2. Worksheet
                       {/GPD}3. Device
                       {/GPP}4. Paper
                       {/GPP}5. Margin
                       {/GPP}6. Chart
                       {/GPS}7. Style

$/GPG /GP

                       ^                   ^
                       ^ /GRAPH PLOT GRAPH ^
                       ^                   ^



     GRAPH - Directs 20/20 to plot, print, or display the current
             graph on the output device that you specify.

     GRAPH is one of /GRAPH PLOT's two action commands.  The other 
     action command is WORKSHEET.

$/GPW /GP

                       ^                       ^
                       ^ /GRAPH PLOT WORKSHEET ^
                       ^                       ^



      WORKSHEET - Directs 20/20 to plot, print, or display the current
                  worksheet screen (including any graphs) on the output
                  device that you specify.

      WORKSHEET is one of /GRAPH PLOT's two action commands.  The other 
      action command is GRAPH.

$/GPD /GP

                       ^                    ^
                       ^ /GRAPH PLOT DEVICE ^
                       ^                    ^


     DEVICE - Allows you to select the output device.  The choices 
              depend on your system configuration, and can include 
              plotters, printers, or color monitors.  See Appendix A 
              of the 20/20 Handbook for details.

$/GPP /GP

                  ^ /GRAPH PLOT PAPER, MARGIN, CHART ^

   Plots any size image to any location on the page.

     PAPER -  Sets the height and width (in inches) of the paper
              or screen onto which you plot.

     MARGIN - Sets the top and left margins (in inches) around the
              plotted image.  Some devices measure the MARGIN 
              settings from the edges of the paper or screen; others
              have a built-in margin to which the MARGIN settings 
              are added.  Check your output device manual.

     CHART  - Sets the height and width (in inches) of the image.
              The CHART dimension plus the MARGIN can not exceed the 
              PAPER setting.

    Each configured device has default PAPER, MARGIN, and CHART settings
    that appear when you select the commands.

$/GPS /GP

                         ^                   ^
                         ^ /GRAPH PLOT STYLE ^
                         ^                   ^


      STYLE - Specifies quality of plot.  Options are:

          DRAFT      - Generally high speed plotting with coarse shading

          PRODUCTION - Generally low speed plotting with fine shading

      Check your output device manual for more information. 

$/GF /G

                          ^                    ^
                          ^ FORM SPECIFICATION ^
                          ^                    ^

     /GRAPH FORM sets the graph type. The FORM specification options are:

     LINE        - Constructs a single or multiple line graph.  LINE is the
                   default.
 
     BAR         - Constructs a vertical BAR graph.

     COMPARISON  - Arranges data in a series of adjacent bar graphs,
                   allowing data COMPARISON.

     STACKED     - Graphs data in layered bars by STACKing each data item
                   proportionally.

$/GR /G

                     
                          ^                     ^
                          ^ RANGE SPECIFICATION ^
                          ^                     ^



   RANGE - Specifies the range of cells that contain the worksheet
           data to be graphed.

   DO NOT include labels or empty cells in the range.  The range
   can be any valid range, including non-contiguous.
 
   Reference:   {CRRG}1. Cell Ranges

$/GW /G

                         ^ WINDOW SPECIFICATION ^

      WINDOW - Specifies the display window for your graph.

      NOTE: You must use the /WINDOW command to create multiple 
      windows BEFORE you use /GRAPH WINDOW to display graphics 
      in multiple windows.

      When you select /GRAPH WINDOW, a list of possible window 
      locations appears, each preceded by a number.

      The default window location (adjacent to the current window) 
      is highlighted.  The window locations are listed in left-to-right, 
      top-to-bottom order.  Select the default window by typing <CR>.
      Select a different window by typing the number that precedes the
      listed window location (for example, type 1 to select 1-top, etc.);
      or use use the arrow keys to move to the listed window location, 
      then type <CR>.

$/GG /G

                          ^                    ^
                          ^ GRID SPECIFICATION ^
                          ^                    ^

      GRID - Designates the desired markings for the vertical axis.  The
             options are:

           TICKS - A tick mark appears on the vertical axis, to the 
                   right of each vertical value.  This is the default.

           LINE  - A horizontal line appears across the graph for each
                   row value.

           NONE  - No markings appear on the vertical axis, and no lines
                   are drawn.

$/GO /G

                          ^ ORDER SPECIFICATION ^

     ORDER - Specifies whether the contents of the graph are presented by
             column or row information.  You can choose:

          COLUMN - The data presented in the spreadsheet colummns is 
                   placed on the graph's vertical axis, and the row data 
                   becomes the like-shaded portions in the graph.  This 
                   is the default.

          ROW    - The data presented in the spreadsheet rows is placed on
                   the graph's vertical axis, and the column data becomes
                   the like-shaded portions.  

     If the range contains only one row or column of data, ORDER is 
     ignored, and the vertical axis contains the axis of data that is
     greater than one.

$/GT /G

                          ^ TITLE SPECIFICATION ^

        TITLE - Sets the graph title.  Options are:

            NONE   - No subtitle appears on the graph, or the existing
                     title is erased.  This is the default.

            TOP    - Places the title at the top of the graph.

            BOTTOM - Places the title at the bottom of the graph.

            Suboptions are:   

                     MANUAL - You type in the title you choose.

                     RANGE  - You type in the range that contains 
                              the label you want to use as a title.

$/GS /G

                          ^                    ^
                          ^ SUBT SPECIFICATION ^
                          ^                    ^

      SUBT - Creates a graph subtitle.  Options are:

           NONE   - No subtitle appears on the graph, or
                    the existing subtitle is erased.  This is
                    the default.

           TOP    - Places the subtitle at the top of the graph.

           BOTTOM - Places the subtitle at the bottom of the graph.

       NOTE:  If you choose the same location for TITLE and SUBT, 
       the subtitle appears below the title.  

$/GL /G

                      ^ LABELS SPECIFICATION - 1 ^

  LABELS - Sets the names for each of the reference points on the graph's
           axes.  Options are:

           AUTOMATIC - 20/20 automatically enters the graph labels,
                       using the graphed data's column and row labels.
              
           MANUAL    - You type in the labels, separating each with 
                       a backslash (\).  For example, \Jan\Feb\Mar.

           RANGE     - You type in the one-dimensional, left-to-right,
                       range of cells that contains the desired labels.

                   See NEXT screen for more

#/GLO /G

                       ^ LABELS SPECIFICATION - 2 ^

      COLUMN or ROW  - You type in column or row labels independently.  
                       Options are: NONE, AUTOMATIC, MANUAL, and RANGE,
                       which are identical to the like-named /GRAPH 
                       LABEL options, except that they affect columns 
                       OR rows, instead of columns AND rows.

               NONE  - No labels appear on the graph, or the existing
                       label is erased.  This is the default.

$/GH /G

                          ^ HEADING SPECIFICATION ^

       HEADING assigns categorical names to labels on either axis.
       /GRAPH HEADING options are:

         NONE    - No heading is assigned, or the existing heading
                   is erased.  This is the initial default.

         COLUMN  - Affects column or row headings.  
         or ROW    Options are: 

                 NONE   - No heading is assigned, or the existing
                          heading is erased. This is the default.
                          
                 MANUAL - You type in the heading.
 
                 RANGE  - You type in a cell that contains a label.  
                          The label becomes the heading.

$/GA /G

                             ^                    ^
                             ^ AXIS SPECIFICATION ^
                             ^                    ^

         AXIS - Sets the vertical range of values to be graphed.  Options
                are:

            AUTOMATIC  - 20/20 automatically sets the low end of the
                         scale at zero (unless there is negative data),
                         and sets the high end of the scale to include
                         the maximum value in the range.
                         
            MANUAL     - You type in the lowest value to be graphed, 
                         then the highest value to be graphed.  


            NOTE:  AXIS designations do not apply to Pie charts.

$/GN /G

                             ^ NAME SPECIFICATION ^

         NAME  - Names the graph so that it can be saved for later use.
                 Options are:

             SAVE   - Saves the graph that you name.  You can save as many 
                      as five graphs with each worksheet. 

             REDRAW - Redraws the specified graph.

             GET    - Sets the specified graph options as defaults.

             DELETE - Deletes the specified graph.

             ERASE  - Deletes all graphs stored with the current worksheet.

             LIST   - Lists all graphs stored with the current worksheet.

$/H /

                                  ^      ^
                                  ^ HELP ^
                                  ^      ^

       Provides information about worksheet concepts, 20/20 commands,
       and functions.

       Type "?" from any screen for more information about the HELP utility.

$/M /

                                 ^        ^
                                 ^ MODIFY ^
                                 ^        ^

          Modifies the worksheet in the following ways:

   {/MB}1. BLANK   -  Erases the value, formula, and format of a cell or
                      cell range.

   {/MC}2. CLEAR   -  Erases the contents of all the cells in the worksheet.

   {/MD}3. DELETE  -  Deletes entire columns or rows from the worksheet.

   {/MI}4. INSERT  -  Inserts entire columns or rows into the worksheet.

   {/MM}5. MOVE    -  Moves an entire column or row from one worksheet
                      location to another.

$/MB /M

                                ^              ^
                                ^ MODIFY BLANK ^
                                ^              ^




         BLANK - Erases the value, formula, and format of a cell or 
                 cell range.

         CAUTION:  Once cells are blanked, they cannot be recovered.

$/MC /M

                             ^ MODIFY CLEAR ^

       CLEAR - Affects the worksheet in the following ways:

            o  All memory occupied by the worksheet is released
            o  /DEFAULT and /FORMAT options are reset to default status
            o  /STORAGE LINK and /GRAPH settings are cleared
            o  The cell cursor is positioned at [0,0]
            o  Titles and multiple window settings are cleared

       The following /OPTION command settings remain unchanged:

            o  AUTO-MOVE (automatic cell cursor movement)
            o  NAMES (cell referencing by cell names)
            o  ORDER (recalculation order)
            o  RECALC (recalculation method)
            o  TERMINAL (terminal characteristics)

$/MD /M

                             ^ MODIFY DELETE ^

       DELETE - Erases entire columns or rows from the worksheet, 
                beginning at the current cell cursor position.  

       ALWAYS position the cell cursor at the column or row you want to 
       move before you use /MODIFY DELETE.

       20/20 adjusts all cell references (including fixed, mixed, and
       relative) within each formula, thereby maintaining correct 
       references to cells that have shifted because columns or rows
       have been deleted.

       CAUTION:  If you reference a cell in a column or row that you
       have deleted, an error message (indicating the location of the
       now erroneous formula) appears the next time you recalculate
       the worksheet.  Edit or remove the formula before you proceed.

$/MI /M

                             ^               ^
                             ^ MODIFY INSERT ^
                             ^               ^

       INSERT - Inserts entire columns or rows into the worksheet, 
                beginning at the current cell cursor position.  

       ALWAYS position the cell cursor at the column or row where you want 
       to insert columns or rows before you use /MODIFY INSERT.

       20/20 adjusts all cell references within each formula so that the
       correct reference to shifted cells is maintained.  In addition,
       ranges are expanded to include new columns or rows inserted within
       the range.  The same adjustment is made whether the reference is 
       fixed or relative.

$/MM /M

                              ^ MODIFY MOVE ^

  MOVE - Moves an entire column or row from one worksheet location to another.

  ALWAYS position the cell cursor on the column or row you want to move before
  you use /MODIFY MOVE.  20/20 adjusts cell references within each formula so 
  that the correct reference to shifted cells is maintained.  Formula ranges 
  are expanded or contracted to include new columns or rows, inserted/deleted
  within the range.  Formulas that contain ranges are adjusted as follows:
 
       ----------------------------------------------------------
       | Column or row is moved out of range | Range contracts  |
       |--------------------------------------------------------|
       | Column or row is moved into range   | Range expands    |
       |--------------------------------------------------------|
       | The first or last column or row of  | -1 is substituted|
       | the range is moved                  | into the range   |
       ---------------------------------------------------------- 

$/O /

                                 ^ OPTION ^

      Sets 20/20 functional features.  The Mini-HELP line displays the
      following status information :

               o  Amount of memory used by the model (in bytes)
               o  Default column width and lock status
               o  Recalculation order and method

      /OPTION command options are:

                  {/OA}1. AUTO-MOVE
                  {/OT}2. TERMINAL
                  {/OO}3. ORDER
                  {/OR}4. RECALC
                  {/ON}5. NAMES
                  {/OJ}6. JOURNAL ECHO

$/OA /O

                            ^                  ^
                            ^ OPTION AUTO-MOVE ^
                            ^                  ^




      AUTO-MOVE - Automatically moves the cell cursor in the direction
                  of the last arrow key typed, each time you press <CR>.


$/OT /O

                            ^ OPTION TERMINAL ^

  TERMINAL - Sets the terminal type. The default terminal type is DEC VT100
             (unless you or your system manager specify another default
             terminal).  At the "Terminal" prompt, type the terminal code,
             then <CR>.  Refer to the following list for your terminal code:

                TERMINAL                CODE            GRAPHICS

                DEC VT100 or VT 101     VT100
                DEC VT100 (132 column)  VT100W
                DEC VT125               VT125             Yes
                DEC VT125 (132 column)  VT125W            Yes
                DEC VT220               VT220
                DEC VT220 (132 column)  VT220W
                DEC VT240 or VT241      VT240             Yes
                DEC VT240 (132 column)  VT240W            Yes
                Tektronics 4105         TEK4105           Yes 

$/OO /O

                              ^              ^
                              ^ OPTION ORDER ^
                              ^              ^

      ORDER - Sets the order in which cells are calculated.  The options are:

      NATURAL  - Each cell is evaluated after all the cells which it
                 references are evaluated.

      COLUMN   - Evaluation begins at cell [0,0] and proceeds across
                 columns one at a time, beginning with the first column.

      ROW      - Evaluation begins at cell [0,0] and proceeds down
                 rows one at a time, beginning with the first row.

      NOTE:  Use COLUMN or ROW order to correctly evaluate circular or
      recursive references.  20/20's default calculation order is
      NATURAL.

$/OR /O

                             ^               ^
                             ^ OPTION RECALC ^
                             ^               ^

      RECALC - Sets the method by which cells are calculated.  The options
               are:

      AUTOMATIC - 20/20 evaluates the entire worksheet whenever you
                  change the contents of a cell, or when you press 
                  <CALC> (as the first character) at the Ready: prompt.
    
      MANUAL    - 20/20 evaluates the entire worksheet only when you
                  press <CALC>.  MANUAL eliminates time-consuming 
                  recalculation, when many changes are to be made, 
                  by postponing recalculation until you are ready to 
                  compute any number of changes at one time.  This 
                  is the initial default.

$/ON /O

                              ^ OPTION NAMES ^
                              
 NAMES - Enables you to use cell names as cell references.  Labels in 
         column 0 become row names and labels in row 0 become column names.  
         You can use cell name references in formulas or command files.  
         However, you must observe the following guidelines:

        o  Use no more than the label's first 15 characters
        o  Enter an underscore in place of any non-alphanumeric 
             character in the column or row label
        o  Precede the label with an underscore if its first 
             character is numeric
        o  Enter the label's blank spaces as underscores.
      
 Note:  You can always use cell reference names instead of cell reference 
 numbers.  Cell reference names and cell reference numbers can also be used 
 interchangeably.  Reference: {CRCN}1. Cell Name References

$/OJ /O

                             ^                     ^
                             ^ OPTION JOURNAL ECHO ^
                             ^                     ^   

     JOURNAL ECHO - Enables you to create a file that stores 20/20 commands
                    in command file sequence.  /OPTION JOURNAL ECHO prompts
                    for a filename.  All subsequent entries are stored in
                    this file, until you use /OPTION JOURNAL ECHO to close 
                    the file.

     NOTE:  The journal file contains only what you specify.  For example,
     if you type <CR> to accept default specifications, only the <CR> is
     stored.  
      
$/P /

                                 ^ PRINT ^

  PRINT - Sends all or part of a worksheet to a printer or to a file, and
          sets printer defaults.  The options are:
          
     DEVICE - Changes the default printer or file name. 
                                     
     LENGTH - Changes the default page length. When printing a report, a form
              feed is automatically generated at the end of each page.  The 
              default page length is 63 lines.

     WIDTH  - Changes the default page width.  The default is 80 characters.

     PRINT  - Creates a print file and a printout from a range of worksheet
              cells.
               
$/Q /

                                  ^      ^
                                  ^ QUIT ^
                                  ^      ^

      Quits a 20/20 session.  20/20 prompts for confirmation before actually
      quitting.

      If you have not stored your worksheet, and want to use it again in the
      future, be sure to store it (with /STORAGE WRITE) before you quit, or
      it will be lost.

      NOTE: QUIT is included on every 20/20 command option and sub-option
      level, and like <BKO>, brings you back to your current command option
      level or to Ready:.  Only the /QUIT command exits from a 20/20 session.

$/S /

                              ^ STORAGE  ^

      Stores and retrieves information to or from files.  Options are:

 {/SR}1. READ    - Reads a previously saved worksheet into the current worksheet
 {/SW}2. WRITE   - Writes the current worksheet into a disk file
 {/SC}3. CUT     - Writes a range of worksheet cells into a disk file    
 {/SP}4. PASTE   - Adds all or part of a worksheet file to the current worksheet
 {/SI}5. IMPORT  - Reads a data file into the current worksheet
 {/SE}6. EXPORT  - Creates a data file from the current worksheet
 {/SF}7. FILES   - Manages files for 20/20
 {/SL}8. LINK    - Overlays data from a stored worksheet onto current worksheet

$/SR /S

                            ^              ^
                            ^ STORAGE READ ^
                            ^              ^

       READ - Clears the worksheet currently displayed, and reads in a 
              previously saved worksheet.  20/20 prompts for the filename 
              of the worksheet to be read in.

       The worksheet to be read in must have been saved with either:

                   {/SW}1. /STORAGE WRITE  or
                   {/SC}2. /STORAGE CUT

$/SW /S

                            ^ STORAGE WRITE ^  

     WRITE - Writes the current worksheet into a disk file.
             The information that is saved includes:

              DATA                   FORMAT
                   Values                 Default format
                   Text                   Individual cell formats
                   Titles                 Column widths
                   Names option
                   Formulas          SCREEN DISPLAY
                                          Windows
              RECALCULATION               Cursor location
                   Method
                   Order             GRAPHS
                                          Current graphs
              DATABASE                    Saved (named) graphs
                   Defined links

$/SC /S

                           ^ STORAGE CUT ^

  CUT - Writes a range of cells from the current worksheet into a disk file.  
        20/20 prompts for the filename and range.  Information saved includes:

        DATA                   FORMAT
           Values                 Default format
           Text and Titles        Individual cell formats
           NAMES option           Column widths
           Formulas            
                               SCREEN DISPLAY
        RECALCULATION             Cursor location and Windows 
           Method and Order
                               GRAPHS
        DATABASE                  Current graphs
           Defined links          Saved (named) graphs

                 See Also: {/SP}1. /STORAGE PASTE

$/SP /S

                             ^               ^
                             ^ STORAGE PASTE ^
                             ^               ^

      PASTE - Adds all or part of a stored worksheet to the current
              worksheet.  20/20 prompts for:

           o  Filename of the worksheet to be read in
           o  Input range of cells to be copied from this file
           o  Target range of cells where the range is to appear.

      Pasted cells assume the default characteristics of the current
      worksheet.

      NOTE:  /STORAGE PASTE operates only on contiguous ranges of cells.

               See Also: {/SC}1. STORAGE CUT

$/SI /S

                             ^ STORAGE IMPORT ^  

  IMPORT - Reads data files into the current worksheet at the current cursor 
           location.  These files may have been created by /STORAGE EXPORT
           or by a text editor.  All options overwrite current worksheet data:

    {/SIM}1. MODEL     - Creates a model from a command file created by 
                         /STORAGE EXPORT MODEL.

    {/SIC}2. COMMANDS  - Executes a command file created by /STORAGE EXPORT
                         TEXT or by a text editor.

    {/SID}3. DATA      - Reads values and text from delimited data files 
                         into the current worksheet.

    {/SIT}4. TEXT      - Reads text from a data file as long labels.

    {/SIN}5. NUMBERS   - Reads numbers from a data file.

$/SIC /SI

                        ^                         ^
                        ^ STORAGE IMPORT COMMANDS ^
                        ^                         ^

   IMPORT COMMANDS - Runs a command file created with /STORAGE EXPORT TEXT or
                     a text editor.  The following options set the display 
                     action of the command file:

               QUIET  - Does not update the screen display until the command
                        file pauses, finishes, or changes display action.

               NORMAL - Shows changes on screen as they occur, but does not 
                        show commands or entries in the header.

              VERBOSE - Shows changes on screen and on header as they occur.

                 Reference:   {/SET}1. /STORAGE EXPORT TEXT

$/SID /SI

                          ^                     ^
                          ^ STORAGE IMPORT DATA ^
                          ^                     ^

   IMPORT DATA - Imports values and text from a data file.  The fields in 
                 the file can be separated by a delimiter character, or
                 can have known fixed widths.  Options are:
        
        DELIMITED - The fields in the file are separated by a delimiter
                    character (the default is #) which you enter when
                    prompted.  Delimited files are created by /STORAGE
                    EXPORT DATA. 

          FIXED   - The fields in the file have fixed widths that must
                    match the column widths into which the fields are 
                    read.  If the field and column widths do not match,
                    the file is not imported correctly.


$/SIM /SI

                        ^                      ^
                        ^ STORAGE IMPORT MODEL ^
                        ^                      ^

   IMPORT MODEL - Creates a model from a command file created by /STORAGE 
                  EXPORT MODEL.  The following options set the display
                  action of the command file:

          QUIET   - Does not update screen display until command file 
                    pauses, finishes, or changes display action.

          NORMAL  - Shows changes on screen as they occur, but does not
                    show commands or entries in header.

          VERBOSE - Shows changes on screen and on header as they occur.

               Reference:   {/SEM}1. /STORAGE EXPORT MODEL

$/SIN /SI

                         ^                        ^
                         ^ STORAGE IMPORT NUMBERS ^
                         ^                        ^



   IMPORT NUMBERS - Reads numbers from a data file into cells in the 
                    current worksheet, starting at the current cursor
                    location.  Successive rows of data file numbers 
                    are entered in successive rows of the worksheet. 
                    All non-numeric data is ignored.

$/SIT /SI

                           ^                     ^
                           ^ STORAGE IMPORT TEXT ^
                           ^                     ^

  IMPORT TEXT - Reads text from a data file into the current worksheet.
                Text is read in as left-justified labels, starting at 
                the current cursor location.

      NOTE:  If a left-justified label extends into a non-blank cell, 
      the label display is truncated.  To display the entire label, 
      blank the non-blank cell or insert a new column of blank cells.

$/SE /S

                             ^                ^
                             ^ STORAGE EXPORT ^
                             ^                ^

    EXPORT - Creates data files in one of the following formats:
         
       {/SEM}1. MODEL  - Creates a command file of 20/20 commands that
                         can be transported between computer systems.

       {/SED}2. DATA   - Creates a delimited data file (of the numbers 
                         and text in the current worksheet) that can be
                         transported to other software packages.

       {/SET}3. TEXT   - Creates a data file format (of worksheet labels 
                         and numbers) that can be read by a text editor.
                         Also creates 20/20 command files. 

$/SET /SE

                          ^ STORAGE EXPORT TEXT ^

    EXPORT TEXT - Creates 20/20 text file formats that can be read by 
                  text editors.  Also creates 20/20 command files which
                  execute procedures that you define.  You list these 
                  procedures (as left-justified labels) in each successive 
                  row of column 0.

          RANGE:  Enter a range that includes column 0, as well as all
