                                 ^  TOOLS  ^

      Performs data utility, project scheduling, and goalseeking
      operations.  Options are:

     {/TD}1. DATABASE   - Sorts, finds, extracts, and performs mathematical/
                          statistical operations on worksheet data.

     {/TT}2. TIMECHART  - Manages time-scheduled projects by returning time
                          allocations based on data that you enter and units
                          of time that you select. 

     {/TG}3. GOALSEEK   - Manipulates the value of a variable cell, either
                          until a desired value in a target (goal) cell is
                          reached, or until convergence ceases.

     {/TS}4. SYSTEM     - Enables you to execute a DCL command from within 
                          20/20.

$/TD /T

                             ^                ^
                             ^ TOOLS DATABASE ^
                             ^                ^

        {/TDS}1. SORT     - Sorts alphanumeric data by column or row.

        {/TDF}2. FIND     - Searches the database and identifies the data
                            that matches the specified criteria.  Displays
                            TRUE, if a match occurs.

        {/TDE}3. EXTRACT  - Selects data matched by FIND, and writes the
                            data to other worksheet locations.

        {/TDO}4. OPERATE  - Performs mathematical and statistical operations
                            on data matched by FIND, and writes the results
                            to other spreadsheet locations.

$/TDS /TD

                            ^                     ^
                            ^ TOOLS DATABASE SORT ^
                            ^                     ^

    DATABASE SORT - Sorts data from a range of cells to a specified target 
                    range.  Rows are sorted based on a key column, and
                    columns are sorted based on a key row.

                    Sort in ascending or descending order.  In ascending
                    order, the following rules apply:

                        First  - Text (in ASCII order)
                        Second - Values (in numeric order)
                        Third  - Blank cells

         NOTE:  The target range must not overlap the source range.  If a
         cell in the source range contains a formula, only the calculated
         value is moved to the target range.

$/TDF /TD

                            ^                     ^
                            ^ TOOLS DATABASE FIND ^
                            ^                     ^

    DATABASE FIND - Finds and identifies data in the database that matches 
                    specified criteria.  A database is a collection of 
                    information, identified by fields and records.  Fields
                    list information by class, such as name, city, ZIP 
                    code, etc.  A record contains one entry in each field.

                    In 20/20, fields are columns and rows are records.  Data
                    can be text, numbers, or formulas.   

                    NOTE:  FIND must precede EXTRACT and OPERATE.
                             
# /TD

                       ^ TOOLS DATABASE FIND CRITERIA ^

     FIND uses one or more criteria to identify records.  Criteria are
     formulas that use logical operators to compare the following:
    
             o The contents of a cell with the contents of a cell
             o The contents of a cell value with a number, and/or
             o A cell value with a character string.

     Criteria are entered in empty columns on the same row as the first
     record in the database.  Each criterion must contain a cell refer-
     ence to a field in the first record.

     20/20 prompts for the criteria range.  This is the range of columns
     that contain the criteria, and the range of database rows to be
     searched.  Any or all of the criteria can be selected.

# /TD

             ^ TOOLS DATABASE FIND CRITERIA EXAMPLES - USE ^

      ^  /....0/......1/....2/............3/............4/............5/^
      ^ 0^  NAME  BADGE#   DIV     CRITERION     CRITERION  CRITERION
      ^ 1^  John      81   ENG      [1,1]>90    [2,1]="EN" [2,1]=[$5,$0]
      ^ 2^  Bill     302   ADM
      ^ 3^   Sue     111   FIN

   In this example, the criteria range is:  criteria - columns 3 and 4
                                            search   - rows 1 through 3

   The result is:

      ^  /....0/......1/....2/............3/............4/............5/^
      ^ 0^  NAME  BADGE#   DIV     CRITERION     CRITERION  CRITERION
      ^ 1^  John      81   ENG                        TRUE
      ^ 2^  Bill     302   ADM          TRUE
      ^ 3^   Sue     111   FIN          TRUE

$/TDE /TD

                          ^ TOOLS DATABASE EXTRACT ^

    DATABASE EXTRACT - Copies data (matched by FIND) from the database to
                       another worksheet location.  Any or all data matched
                       by FIND can be extracted.   20/20 prompts for the:

            Source Range   - the location of the data to be extracted
            Target Range   - the location where the extracted data is to go
            Criteria Range - the location of the columns containing the
                              criteria formulas and the results of FIND.

       If a source cell contains a formula, a reference to the source cell
       is entered in the target cell.  Therefore, changes in the calculated
       value of the source cell will be reflected in the target cell.

       NOTE:  You can specify more than one criterion column by using a
       logical operator, such as <AND> or <OR>.

# /TD

                     ^ TOOLS DATABASE EXTRACT EXAMPLES ^

        ^  /....0/......1/....2/............3/............4/............5/^
 ^ 0^  NAME  BADGE#   DIV     CRITERION     CRITERION  CRITERION
 ^ 1^  John      81   ENG                        TRUE
 ^ 2^  Bill     302   ADM          TRUE
 ^ 3^   Sue     111   FIN          TRUE

       In this example, source   - columns ^NAME^ and ^DIV^, rows 1..3
                        criteria - column 3  ([1,1]>90)

       yields:         ^Bill | ADM^ and ^Sue | FIN^

       and,             source   - columns ^NAME^ and ^DIV^, rows 1..3
                        criteria - column 4  ([2,1]="EN")

       yields:         ^JOHN | ENG^

$/TDO /TD

                        ^ TOOLS DATABASE OPERATE ^

  DATABASE OPERATE - Performs calculations on data matched by FIND.  20/20
                     prompts for the:

      Source Range   - range that lists the data on which the operation 
                        occurs (specify only one column for each operation) 
      Target Cell    - leftmost cell location where the results are to go
      Criteria Range - location of the columns containing the criteria
                        formulas and the results of the FIND operation.

      AVERAGE - Averages the values of the cells matched by FIND.
      DISTRIB - Counts the number of records matched by FIND.
      HIGH    - Returns the maximum value of the cells matched by FIND.
      LOW     - Returns the minimum value of the cells matched by FIND.
      SUM     - Sums the value of the cells matched by FIND.

$/TG /T

                             ^                ^
                             ^ TOOLS GOALSEEK ^
                             ^                ^

     GOALSEEK - Reaches a goal by adjusting the value of a specified
                cell in the model.  GOALSEEK employs three elements:

             o Variable Cell - contains the value that 20/20 manipulates
             o Target Cell   - contains a formula whose calculated value
                                is dependent on the variable cell
             o Goal          - the value that the target cell is to reach.

         20/20 adjusts the value in the variable cell while recalculating 
         the worksheet.  This modifies the value of the target cell.  20/20
         then compares this value to the goal value until convergence is
         reached, or until 20/20 determines that the goal is unreachable.

$/TT /T

^                 ^ Manages time-scheduled projects by returning time
^ TOOLS TIMECHART ^ allocations based upon data entered.  You determine 
^                 ^ the units of time. 

        The following chart shows a TIMECHART MODEL:

             ^  /.......1/........2/.......3/...3/....4/....5/....6/^
             ^ 0^     TASK     PRED1    PRED2 TIME START   END SLACK
             ^ 1^
             ^ 2^   DESIGN                      30     0    30    12
             ^ 3^ MATERIAL                      42     0    42     0
             ^ 4^    FOUND     DESIGN MATERIAL  35    42    77     0

        TIMECHART calculates three elements:

             o  Start time - The time each task is to begin.
             o  End time   - The time of task completion.
             o  Slack time - The amount of time a task can be delayed
                              without affecting the task it precedes.

$/TS /T
